msContents.summary: Complete copy of the Qurʼān with interlinear Persian translation and extensive marginal comments.
msContents.textLang: Arabic with Persian translation and marginal comments

author.name: Free Library of Philadelphia. Rare Book Department. John Frederick Lewis collection of Oriental Manuscripts

respStmt.persName: Mīr Maḥmūd walad Mīr Muḥammad ʻAlī
مير محمود ولد مير محمد على.

supportDesc.extent: 392 leaves : 285 x 165 (210 x 115) mm bound to 290 x 185 mm
supportDesc.foliation: Modern foliation in pencil added, top left recto; catchwords every verso, lower left.

layoutDesc.layout: 11 long lines with Persian in between each line; border- and line-ruled.

scriptDesc.scriptNote: Written in naskh in black ink, pointed and vocalized with Persian in nastaʻliq in red and black ink, pointed.

decoDesc.decoNote: Dual page illumination in gold, red, and blue on first opening (f. 1v-2r) with text in cloudbands. Textblock rule-bordered in gold and black, with an outer frame-rule in gold to contain marginalia. Line rules in gold between each line of the source-text and the translation. Textblock tinted beige. Sūrah titles in black ink on a gold background. Readings and marked text divisions in red; gold roundels mark verse ends. Gold circular medallions outlined and decorated with finials in blue in the margins also indicate textual divisions.

binding.p: Rebound in light brown leather over pasteboard with flap (Type II). The (possibly) original outside cover decorations of red leather with gold tooled sets of frames are attached to the outer boards; along with a matching piece of gold tooled red leather along the foredge flap. Doublure of reddish-brown leather.

origin.p: Copy is undated, but likely made in the mid-17th to mid-18th century, possibly in South Asia. The scribe gives his name as "Mīr Maḥmūd walad Mīr Muḥammad ʻAlī ibn Mīr Qāsim ibn Mīr Ḥusayn ibn Mīr Aḥmad ibn Mīr Saʻīd, ibn Mīr Ḥājjī ibn Mīr Sayyid Ḥusayn Qumī, Ridawī, Taqawī who now rests in peace in the city of Kashmir" (f. 392r).

history.provenance: Gift of Anne Baker Lewis in 1933.
Formerly owned by John Frederick Lewis.

surface.n: Back cover flap opened to show design
Fore edge flap closed, inside front cover
